04496nam a22007215i 9780231504003DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20002000nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802315040037 a10.7312/addi116562doi  a(DE-B1597)458578  a(OCoLC)979574221  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aPL806.K75Z53 2000 7aLIT0080302bisacsh1 aAddiss, Stephen, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aOld Taoist :bThe Life, Art, and Poetry of Kodojin (1865-1944) /cStephen Addiss, Jonathan Chaves, J. Thomas Rimer. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2000] 4c©2000  a1 online resource (208 p.) :b25 halftones, 8 color plates  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface and Acknowledgments -- t1. Kodōjin’s Life and Art -- t2. Kodōjin’s Japanese Poetry -- t3 Kodōjin and the T’ao Ch’ien. Tradition in Kanshi Poetry -- t4. Kodōjin’s Chinese Poetry -- tA. Note on Kodōjin and the Art and Literature of His Period -- tEpilogue -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the literary and artistic milieu of early modern Japan the Chinese and Japanese arts flourished side by side. Kodojin, the "Old Taoist" (1865-1944), was the last of these great poet-painters in Japan. Under the support of various patrons, he composed a number of Taoist-influenced Chinese and Japanese poems and did lively and delightful ink paintings, continuing the tradition of the poet-sage who devotes himself to study of the ancients, lives quietly and modestly, and creates art primarily for himself and his friends.Portraying this last representative of a tradition of gentle and refined artistry in the midst of a society that valued economic growth and national achievement above all, this beautifully illustrated book brings together 150 of Kodojin's Chinese poems (introduced and translated by Jonathan Chaves), more than 100 of his haiku and tanka (introduced and translated by Stephen Addiss), and many examples of his calligraphy and ink paintings. Addiss's in-depth introduction details the importance of the poet-painter tradition, outlines the life of Kodojin, and offers a critical appraisal of his work, while J. Thomas Rimer's essay puts the literary work of the Old Taoist in context.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aAuthors, Japanesey20th centuryvBiography. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Asian / Japanese.2bisacsh1 aChaves, Jonathan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aChaves, Jonathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChaves, Jonathan.1 aRimer, J. Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRimer, J. Thomas.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044247240uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/addi1165640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231504003423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231504003/original  a978-3-11-044247-2  Columbia University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-064977-2  Asian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagec2000d2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK